    <!-- Decision Guide -->
    <section class="py-16 bg-white">
      <div class="container mx-auto px-4">
        <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto">
          <h2 class="uppercase text-3xl md:text-4xl font-bold text-slate-900 mb-8">
            Choosing the Right Membrane for Your Project
          </h2>

          <div class="space-y-8">
            <!-- New Construction -->
            <div class="bg-slate-50 rounded-xl p-6 border-l-4 border-cyan-500">
              <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-slate-900 mb-3 flex items-center">
                <span class="text-cyan-500 mr-3 text-2xl">🏗️</span>
                New Construction or Major Renovation
              </h3>
              <p class="text-slate-600 mb-3 leading-relaxed">
                <strong>Best Choice:</strong> Sheet membrane (Blueskin WP 200) + dimple drainage board (Delta-MS)
              </p>
              <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed">
                <strong>Why:</strong> You have perfect conditions—clean concrete, optimal timing control, proper staging. Sheet membranes deliver the most reliable long-term performance when properly installed on prepared substrates. Budget $12-18/sq ft for the complete system including materials, labor, and drainage integration.
              </p>
            </div>

            <!-- Existing Foundation -->
            <div class="bg-slate-50 rounded-xl p-6 border-l-4 border-cyan-500">
              <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-slate-900 mb-3 flex items-center">
                <span class="text-cyan-500 mr-3 text-2xl">🏠</span>
                Existing Foundation with Leaking Problems
              </h3>
              <p class="text-slate-600 mb-3 leading-relaxed">
                <strong>Best Choice (exterior access available):</strong> Sheet or liquid-applied membrane + Delta-MS
              </p>
              <p class="text-slate-600 mb-3 leading-relaxed">
                <strong>Alternative (no exterior access):</strong> Interior drainage system with cementitious coating
              </p>
              <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed">
                <strong>Why:</strong> Exterior waterproofing is always preferable—it's the only method that truly prevents water from entering the concrete. Interior systems are compromise solutions for situations where excavation isn't possible. Expect $150-300/linear foot for exterior excavation, membrane, drainage, and backfill.
              </p>
            </div>

            <!-- Historic Property -->
            <div class="bg-slate-50 rounded-xl p-6 border-l-4 border-cyan-500">
              <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-slate-900 mb-3 flex items-center">
                <span class="text-cyan-500 mr-3 text-2xl">🏛️</span>
                Historic Property or Stone Foundation
              </h3>
              <p class="text-slate-600 mb-3 leading-relaxed">
                <strong>Best Choice:</strong> Liquid-applied membrane (Tremco or Sika) + protection board
              </p>
              <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed">
                <strong>Why:</strong> Stone and rubble foundations present irregular surfaces with countless penetrations and transitions. Liquid-applied systems conform perfectly to these surfaces and self-flash around every irregularity. Higher cost ($14-20/sq ft) justified by superior coverage on complex substrates.
              </p>
            </div>

            <!-- Budget Constraints -->
            <div class="bg-slate-50 rounded-xl p-6 border-l-4 border-amber-500">
              <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-slate-900 mb-3 flex items-center">
                <span class="text-amber-500 mr-3 text-2xl">💰</span>
                Budget Constraints
              </h3>
              <p class="text-slate-600 mb-3 leading-relaxed">
                <strong>Minimum Acceptable:</strong> Interior drainage system with cementitious coating
              </p>
              <p class="text-slate-600 mb-3 leading-relaxed">
                <strong>Warning:</strong> Avoid "economy waterproofing" (spray tar, thin poly sheets, paint-on coatings) that promise exterior protection for $3-5/sq ft. These fail quickly in Toronto's climate, and you'll pay twice—once for the failed work, and again for proper waterproofing.
              </p>
              <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed">
                <strong>Our recommendation:</strong> If exterior waterproofing isn't affordable right now, invest in a properly designed interior drainage system ($8-12/sq ft) that actually manages water intrusion. Save for exterior waterproofing and do it right when budget allows. Half-measures waste money.
              </p>
            </div>

            <!-- DIY Considerations -->
            <div class="bg-slate-50 rounded-xl p-6 border-l-4 border-red-500">
              <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-slate-900 mb-3 flex items-center">
                <span class="text-red-500 mr-3 text-2xl">⚠️</span>
                DIY Considerations
              </h3>
              <p class="text-slate-600 mb-3 leading-relaxed">
                <strong>Honest Assessment:</strong> Exterior waterproofing is not a good DIY project for most homeowners.
              </p>
              <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed">
                <strong>Why:</strong> Excavating 8-10 feet deep next to your foundation is dangerous without proper shoring. One mistake in membrane installation (missed seam, improper termination, insufficient overlap) creates a permanent leak path that requires complete re-excavation to fix. Professional installation with warranty costs 30-40% more than DIY materials, but eliminates catastrophic failure risk. This is one area where professional expertise genuinely pays for itself.
              </p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Installation Best Practices -->
    <section class="py-16 bg-slate-50">
      <div class="container mx-auto px-4">
        <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto">
          <h2 class="uppercase text-3xl md:text-4xl font-bold text-slate-900 mb-8">
            Installation Best Practices
          </h2>

          <div class="prose prose-lg max-w-none text-slate-600 mb-8">
            <p class="text-lg leading-relaxed">
              Proper membrane installation is just as critical as membrane selection. Even the highest-quality materials will fail if applied incorrectly. Here are the non-negotiable requirements for successful waterproofing membrane installation in Toronto conditions:
            </p>
          </div>

          <div class="space-y-6">
            <div class="bg-white rounded-xl border border-slate-200/60 p-6">
              <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-slate-900 mb-3">1. Surface Preparation</h3>
              <ul class="space-y-2 text-slate-600">
                <li class="flex items-start">
                  <span class="text-cyan-500 mr-2 mt-1">•</span>
                  <span><strong>Clean and dry:</strong> Remove all dirt, loose concrete, efflorescence, form oil, and curing compounds. Membranes won't bond to contaminated surfaces.</span>
                </li>
                <li class="flex items-start">
                  <span class="text-cyan-500 mr-2 mt-1">•</span>
                  <span><strong>Repair defects:</strong> Fill honeycomb, tie-holes, and voids with hydraulic cement or non-shrink grout before membrane application.</span>
                </li>
                <li class="flex items-start">
                  <span class="text-cyan-500 mr-2 mt-1">•</span>
                  <span><strong>Prime porous surfaces:</strong> Apply appropriate primer to porous concrete or masonry to improve membrane adhesion.</span>
                </li>
              </ul>
            </div>

            <div class="bg-white rounded-xl border border-slate-200/60 p-6">
              <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-slate-900 mb-3">2. Temperature Requirements</h3>
              <ul class="space-y-2 text-slate-600">
                <li class="flex items-start">
                  <span class="text-cyan-500 mr-2 mt-1">•</span>
                  <span><strong>Sheet membranes:</strong> Install when substrate and air temperature are above 5°C (40°F). Adhesive won't bond in cold conditions. In Toronto, this means April-October installation windows.</span>
                </li>
                <li class="flex items-start">
                  <span class="text-cyan-500 mr-2 mt-1">•</span>
                  <span><strong>Liquid-applied:</strong> Follow manufacturer's temperature specifications strictly. Most require 10-25°C and dry conditions for 24-48 hours after application.</span>
                </li>
                <li class="flex items-start">
                  <span class="text-cyan-500 mr-2 mt-1">•</span>
                  <span><strong>Cold weather workaround:</strong> Some contractors use heated enclosures for winter installations. This adds significant cost but enables year-round work.</span>
                </li>
              </ul>
            </div>

            <div class="bg-white rounded-xl border border-slate-200/60 p-6">
              <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-slate-900 mb-3">3. Seams and Overlaps</h3>
              <ul class="space-y-2 text-slate-600">
                <li class="flex items-start">
                  <span class="text-cyan-500 mr-2 mt-1">•</span>
                  <span><strong>Minimum 100mm (4") overlap:</strong> On all sheet membrane seams. Many pros use 150mm for extra security.</span>
                </li>
                <li class="flex items-start">
                  <span class="text-cyan-500 mr-2 mt-1">•</span>
                  <span><strong>Roll seams:</strong> Use a J-roller or hand roller to firmly press laps and eliminate air pockets.</span>
                </li>
                <li class="flex items-start">
                  <span class="text-cyan-500 mr-2 mt-1">•</span>
                  <span><strong>Seal cut edges:</strong> Apply membrane mastic or compatible sealant to all cut edges and terminations.</span>
                </li>
              </ul>
            </div>

            <div class="bg-white rounded-xl border border-slate-200/60 p-6">
              <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-slate-900 mb-3">4. Terminations and Transitions</h3>
              <ul class="space-y-2 text-slate-600">
                <li class="flex items-start">
                  <span class="text-cyan-500 mr-2 mt-1">•</span>
                  <span><strong>Top termination:</strong> Extend membrane to final grade or higher. Mechanically fasten termination bar and seal with compatible caulk.</span>
                </li>
                <li class="flex items-start">
                  <span class="text-cyan-500 mr-2 mt-1">•</span>
                  <span><strong>Footing transition:</strong> Extend membrane onto footing at least 150mm. This creates continuous coverage from footing to grade.</span>
                </li>
                <li class="flex items-start">
                  <span class="text-cyan-500 mr-2 mt-1">•</span>
                  <span><strong>Penetration details:</strong> Boot or wrap all pipes, anchors, and penetrations with membrane, extending at least 150mm beyond the penetration in all directions.</span>
                </li>
              </ul>
            </div>

            <div class="bg-white rounded-xl border border-slate-200/60 p-6">
              <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-slate-900 mb-3">5. Protection and Drainage</h3>
              <ul class="space-y-2 text-slate-600">
                <li class="flex items-start">
                  <span class="text-cyan-500 mr-2 mt-1">•</span>
                  <span><strong>Protection board required:</strong> Never backfill directly against waterproofing membrane. Always install drainage board (Delta-MS) or protection board first.</span>
                </li>
                <li class="flex items-start">
                  <span class="text-cyan-500 mr-2 mt-1">•</span>
                  <span><strong>Proper backfill:</strong> Use clean fill—no rocks, construction debris, or frozen chunks. Hand-place and compact in lifts to avoid damaging membrane.</span>
                </li>
                <li class="flex items-start">
                  <span class="text-cyan-500 mr-2 mt-1">•</span>
                  <span><strong>Drainage integration:</strong> Ensure drainage board connects to functioning weeping tile and sump system. Membrane without drainage = hydrostatic pressure buildup.</span>
                </li>
              </ul>
            </div>

            <div class="bg-white rounded-xl border border-slate-200/60 p-6">
              <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-slate-900 mb-3">6. Quality Control Inspection Points</h3>
              <ul class="space-y-2 text-slate-600">
                <li class="flex items-start">
                  <span class="text-cyan-500 mr-2 mt-1">•</span>
                  <span><strong>Pre-membrane:</strong> Photograph substrate condition and all repairs before membrane application.</span>
                </li>
                <li class="flex items-start">
                  <span class="text-cyan-500 mr-2 mt-1">•</span>
                  <span><strong>During application:</strong> Verify overlap dimensions, seam adhesion, and penetration details as work progresses.</span>
                </li>
                <li class="flex items-start">
                  <span class="text-cyan-500 mr-2 mt-1">•</span>
                  <span><strong>Final inspection:</strong> Walk entire foundation perimeter checking for tears, missed areas, incomplete seams, or protection board damage before backfilling.</span>
                </li>
                <li class="flex items-start">
                  <span class="text-cyan-500 mr-2 mt-1">•</span>
                  <span><strong>Documentation:</strong> Take comprehensive photos of completed membrane before drainage board installation. These become your warranty proof.</span>
                </li>
              </ul>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="mt-8 bg-navy-900 text-white p-6 rounded-xl">
            <h4 class="font-bold text-xl mb-3">Red Flags: Signs of Poor Installation</h4>
            <p class="mb-3">Watch for these warning signs that indicate substandard waterproofing work:</p>
            <ul class="space-y-2">
              <li class="flex items-start">
                <span class="text-amber-500 mr-2">⚠</span>
                <span>Membrane installed in cold weather without heated enclosure</span>
              </li>
              <li class="flex items-start">
                <span class="text-amber-500 mr-2">⚠</span>
                <span>Visible dirt, dust, or moisture on substrate during membrane application</span>
              </li>
              <li class="flex items-start">
                <span class="text-amber-500 mr-2">⚠</span>
                <span>Narrow overlaps (less than 100mm/4 inches)</span>
              </li>
              <li class="flex items-start">
                <span class="text-amber-500 mr-2">⚠</span>
                <span>Unsealed cut edges or terminations</span>
              </li>
              <li class="flex items-start">
                <span class="text-amber-500 mr-2">⚠</span>
                <span>Backfilling directly against membrane without protection board</span>
              </li>
              <li class="flex items-start">
                <span class="text-amber-500 mr-2">⚠</span>
                <span>Rock or construction debris used as backfill material</span>
              </li>
              <li class="flex items-start">
                <span class="text-amber-500 mr-2">⚠</span>
                <span>Contractor rushes through inspection or resists photo documentation</span>
              </li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>
