          <h2 class="uppercase text-3xl md:text-4xl font-bold text-slate-900 mb-8">
            Frequently Asked Questions
          </h2>

          <div class="space-y-6">
            <div class="bg-slate-50 rounded-xl p-6 border-l-4 border-cyan-500">
              <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-slate-900 mb-3">What's the difference between Blueskin and Delta-MS?</h3>
              <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed">
                This is a common confusion—they're completely different products that work together. Blueskin (and similar products like Bakor 790-11) is a waterproofing membrane—a rubberized asphalt sheet that bonds to your foundation and creates a water-impermeable barrier. Delta-MS is a drainage board—a dimpled HDPE plastic sheet that channels water down to the drain tile while protecting the waterproofing membrane from backfill damage. In a proper exterior system, you apply Blueskin first (waterproofing), then Delta-MS over it (drainage + protection). They're complementary, not competing products.
              </p>
            </div>

            <div class="bg-slate-50 rounded-xl p-6 border-l-4 border-cyan-500">
              <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-slate-900 mb-3">Can I use the same membrane for interior and exterior applications?</h3>
              <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed">
                Not effectively. Exterior membranes (like Blueskin) are designed for positive-side waterproofing—applied to the exterior face where they prevent water from entering the concrete. Interior systems work on the negative side (water pressure pushes membrane away from wall) and require different approaches: either drainage systems that capture and redirect water (dimple membrane + perimeter drain), or crystalline coatings that penetrate and waterproof within the concrete itself. You can't simply apply an exterior sheet membrane on the interior—it won't bond under pressure and will eventually delaminate and fail.
              </p>
            </div>

            <div class="bg-slate-50 rounded-xl p-6 border-l-4 border-cyan-500">
              <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-slate-900 mb-3">How long do different waterproofing membranes last in Toronto's climate?</h3>
              <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed">
                <strong>Sheet membranes (Blueskin, Bakor):</strong> 25-30 years when properly installed with protection board. <strong>Liquid-applied systems:</strong> 20-25 years, slightly less than sheet due to thickness variations. <strong>Bentonite clay:</strong> 50+ years documented performance—these actually improve over time as they hydrate and consolidate. <strong>Dimple drainage boards:</strong> 30+ years—HDPE plastic is extremely durable. <strong>Cementitious coatings:</strong> Permanent once cured—they become integral with the concrete. The weak link is usually not membrane failure but ancillary components (failed drain tile, clogged weepers, foundation settling).
              </p>
            </div>

            <div class="bg-slate-50 rounded-xl p-6 border-l-4 border-cyan-500">
              <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-slate-900 mb-3">Is spray-on rubber or tar waterproofing as good as sheet membranes?</h3>
              <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed">
                No, and this is a critical distinction. What you're describing is likely "damp-proofing" (spray-on asphalt emulsion), not true waterproofing. Damp-proofing slows moisture transmission but can't withstand hydrostatic pressure—it'll fail when groundwater rises. True liquid-applied waterproofing membranes (like Tremco TREMproof or Sika) are different—they're spray-on polyurethane or rubberized systems that cure to 40-80 mil thickness and can perform as well as or better than sheet membranes. The problem is identifying what you're actually getting. If a contractor quotes $3-5/sq ft for "spray-on waterproofing," it's probably damp-proofing. True liquid-applied membrane systems cost $6-12/sq ft and require certified applicators. Always verify product specs and installation standards.
              </p>
            </div>

            <div class="bg-slate-50 rounded-xl p-6 border-l-4 border-cyan-500">
              <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-slate-900 mb-3">Can I install waterproofing membrane in winter in Toronto?</h3>
              <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed">
                Sheet membranes (Blueskin, Bakor) won't bond when substrate temperature is below 5°C (40°F)—the adhesive simply doesn't activate in cold conditions. Installing in winter creates a time bomb: the membrane looks fine initially but hasn't actually bonded, and will eventually delaminate. Some contractors build heated enclosures around the foundation to maintain proper temperatures during winter installations—this works but adds $2,000-5,000 to project cost. Your best strategy: plan waterproofing projects for April through October when temperatures reliably exceed installation minimums. Bentonite clay membranes are the exception—they can be installed in freezing conditions since they don't rely on adhesive bonding.
              </p>
            </div>

            <div class="bg-slate-50 rounded-xl p-6 border-l-4 border-cyan-500">
              <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-slate-900 mb-3">What's the best basement waterproofing membrane for Toronto specifically?</h3>
              <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed">
                For Toronto's conditions—freeze-thaw cycles, clay soil, variable water table—the proven standard is <strong>Blueskin WP 200 paired with Delta-MS drainage board</strong>. This combination has the longest track record of reliable performance in our climate, is familiar to virtually all qualified Toronto waterproofing contractors (reducing installation errors), and delivers 25+ years of protection when properly installed. While other systems (liquid-applied, bentonite) can perform equally well in specific situations, the Blueskin + Delta-MS system offers the best balance of proven performance, contractor expertise, warranty availability, and cost-effectiveness for residential applications across the GTA.
              </p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
